  <h2>Why is Online Safety Important?</h2>
  <p>
    The Internet is an amazing place — you can learn, play, create, and connect with people from all over the world. But just like in real life, you need to be careful and smart to stay safe. <strong>Online safety</strong> means knowing how to protect yourself, your personal information, and your feelings when using the Internet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Learning online safety is just as important as learning to look both ways before crossing the street. Let's explore the key rules every kid should know!
  </p>

  <h2>Rule 1: Keep Personal Information Private</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Personal information</strong> is anything that identifies who you are or where you live. You should <em>never</em> share this with strangers online!
  </p>
  <p>What counts as personal information?</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🏠 Your home address</li>
    <li>📞 Your phone number</li>
    <li>🏫 Your school name and location</li>
    <li>📅 Your full birth date</li>
    <li>🖼️ Your full name combined with photos</li>
    <li>🔑 Passwords (never share these with <em>anyone</em> — even friends!)</li>
    <li>💳 Any financial information (bank cards, etc.)</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    🛡️ Rule of thumb: If you wouldn't shout it out in a room full of strangers, don't post it online!
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Rule 2: Stranger Danger Online</h2>
  <p>
    Just like in real life, there are strangers on the Internet. Many online strangers are perfectly fine — but some might pretend to be someone they're not (this is called <strong>catfishing</strong>). Someone claiming to be a 12-year-old could actually be an adult.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Never</strong> agree to meet someone in person that you only know online — without telling a trusted adult first.</li>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Never</strong> send photos of yourself to strangers.</li>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Never</strong> share your location with someone you've only met online.</li>
    <li>✅ <strong>Always</strong> tell a parent or trusted adult if an online stranger makes you uncomfortable.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Rule 3: Create Strong Passwords</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>strong password</strong> protects your accounts (games, email, apps) from hackers. Here's how to make one:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>📏 <strong>At least 12 characters long</strong></li>
    <li>🔤 <strong>Mix of uppercase and lowercase letters</strong> (e.g., AbCd)</li>
    <li>🔢 <strong>Include numbers</strong> (e.g., 5, 9, 3)</li>
    <li>🔣 <strong>Include special characters</strong> (e.g., !, @, #, $)</li>
    <li>🚫 <strong>Never use</strong> your name, birthday, or "password123"</li>
    <li>🎲 <strong>Use a passphrase</strong> — a sentence you can remember, like "ILoveEating3Mangoes!" — easy to remember, hard to guess!</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>Never share your password</strong> with anyone — not even your best friend. Use a different password for each account. A password manager app can help you remember them!
  </p>

  <h2>Rule 4: Think Before You Post</h2>
  <p>
    Anything you post online can be <em>permanent</em>. Even if you delete a photo or message, someone may have already taken a screenshot. Before you post, ask yourself:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>🤔 Would I be happy if my parents, teachers, or grandparents saw this?</li>
    <li>🤔 Could this embarrass me or someone else in the future?</li>
    <li>🤔 Am I sharing any personal information accidentally (like a photo that shows my school name in the background)?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The rule is simple: <strong>If in doubt, don't post it!</strong>
  </p>

  <h2>Rule 5: Recognise Online Scams</h2>
  <p>
    Scammers try to trick people into giving away money or personal information. Common online scams to watch out for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>🎁 <strong>Fake Prizes</strong> — "Congratulations! You've won a free iPhone! Click here to claim it!" (It's a trap!)</li>
    <li>🔗 <strong>Phishing Links</strong> — Fake emails or messages that look like they're from YouTube or Google, asking you to log in. The link steals your password!</li>
    <li>💰 <strong>Free Robux/V-Bucks Scams</strong> — Sites claiming to give free in-game currency. They steal your account instead!</li>
    <li>😱 <strong>Scare Tactics</strong> — Pop-ups saying "Your computer has a virus! Call this number NOW!" (It's fake — close the tab!)</li>
    <li>🎮 <strong>Fake Game Cheats</strong> — Downloads claiming to be cheat codes that actually install viruses.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If something seems <em>too good to be true</em> — it usually is! Always ask a trusted adult before clicking suspicious links.
  </p>

  <h2>Rule 6: Be Kind — Stop Cyberbullying</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Cyberbullying</strong> is when someone uses the Internet to be mean, hurtful, or threatening to another person. This includes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>😢 Sending mean or hurtful messages</li>
    <li>😢 Spreading rumours or lies about someone online</li>
    <li>😢 Excluding someone from online groups on purpose</li>
    <li>😢 Sharing embarrassing photos or videos without permission</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <strong>What to do if you're being cyberbullied:</strong>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>✅ <strong>Don't respond</strong> — responding often makes it worse.</li>
    <li>✅ <strong>Save evidence</strong> — take a screenshot of the mean messages.</li>
    <li>✅ <strong>Block the bully</strong> — most apps and games have block buttons.</li>
    <li>✅ <strong>Tell a trusted adult</strong> — a parent, teacher, or school counsellor.</li>
    <li>✅ <strong>Report it</strong> — use the "Report" button on social media or gaming apps.</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    🌟 The Golden Rule: Treat others online the same way you want to be treated in real life!
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Rule 7: Screen Time and Digital Wellbeing</h2>
  <p>
    Too much screen time can hurt your health — your eyes, sleep, and physical fitness. Here are some healthy habits:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>👁️ Follow the <strong>20-20-20 rule</strong>: Every 20 minutes, look at something 20 feet away for 20 seconds.</li>
    <li>📵 <strong>No screens 1 hour before bed</strong> — blue light from screens messes up your sleep!</li>
    <li>🏃 Take regular breaks to <strong>move and stretch</strong>.</li>
    <li>⏰ Set a <strong>daily screen time limit</strong> — many phones and tablets have this in their settings.</li>
    <li>🌿 Spend time <strong>offline</strong> — playing outside, reading physical books, or hanging out with friends and family.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Rule 8: Use Safe and Trusted Websites</h2>
  <p>Not all websites are safe or trustworthy. Here's how to spot safe websites:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>🔒 Look for <strong>HTTPS</strong> (padlock icon) in the address bar.</li>
    <li>✅ Use websites recommended by your parents or teachers.</li>
    <li>⚠️ Be cautious of websites full of pop-up ads — they might contain malware.</li>
    <li>🔍 Check if the website belongs to a known, trusted organisation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Helpful Resources for Kids' Online Safety</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>🛡️ <strong>CEOP (Child Exploitation and Online Protection)</strong> — UK's dedicated online safety service.</li>
    <li>🌐 <strong>Internet Matters (internetmatters.org)</strong> — Guides for kids and parents on staying safe online.</li>
    <li>📚 <strong>Common Sense Media</strong> — Reviews and advice on apps, games, and websites for kids.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Fun Facts About Online Safety</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>🤯 There are over <strong>1 billion websites</strong> — but many are unsafe or contain misleading information.</li>
    <li>🔐 It takes a hacker less than <strong>1 second</strong> to crack a simple 6-character password made of only numbers!</li>
    <li>📧 About <strong>45% of all emails</strong> sent worldwide are spam or phishing attempts.</li>
    <li>🌍 Cyberbullying affects <strong>1 in 3 young people</strong> online.</li>
    <li>💪 Kids who learn digital literacy are <strong>significantly better</strong> at identifying fake news and scams.</li>
  </ul>

